\begin_layout Subsection
Interaction between QM solute and RISM solvent
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As in the 3D RISM MM theory, the solute potential acting on solvent site
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is derived from the site-specific contribution of a solvent-solute interaction
 defined as the sum of the LJ and Coulomb terms.
 The LJ energy term, 
\begin_inset Formula $U^{\text{LJ}}=4\sum_{i\alpha}\epsilon_{i\alpha}\left[(\sigma_{i\alpha}/r_{i\alpha})^{12}-(\sigma_{i\alpha}/r_{i\alpha})^{6}\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{i\alpha}=|\vec{r}_{i}-\vec{r}_{\alpha}|$
\end_inset

, accounts for short-range repulsion and dispersion interactions and is
 the sum of pairwise site-site contributions as in the MM case.
 Electrostatic interaction between the charge density of the QM solute and
 charged solvent sites reads:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U^{\text{C}}=\int n_{\text{v}}(\vec{r})f_{\text{C}}(|\vec{r}-\vec{r}'|)n_{\text{u}}(\vec{r}')d^{3}rd^{3}r'\label{eq:solute-solvent-interaction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{v}}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}(\vec{r})$
\end_inset

 are the solvent and solute charge densities, respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\text{C}}(r)=1/r$
\end_inset

 is the Coulomb kernel.
 In self-consistent calculation this expression for the electrostatic interactio
ns is used to define two types of potentials, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{u}}=f_{\text{C}}\ast n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{v}}=f_{\text{C}}\ast n_{\text{v}}$
\end_inset

, acting on charged solvent sites or solute charges (such as electrons),
 respectively.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evaluation strategy for these two potentials differs slightly due to
 the nature of the charge densities 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{v}}$
\end_inset

.
 The solvent charge density, when it appears in an expression for solvent
 electrostatic potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{v}}$
\end_inset

, has a meaning of a statistically average charge density, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{v}}=\rho\sum_{\alpha}q_{\alpha}h_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

; it carries net zero charge (for neutral solutes) and is represented on
 a uniform Cartesian grid.
 The corresponding potential is obtained by solving Poisson equation with
 periodic boundary conditions using fast Fourier transform.
 For neutral solutes with typical dipole moments and large periodic cells
 this may be justified 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Makov95"

\end_inset

; an estimate of the magnitude of the dipole correction for our systems
 is 0.1 kcal/mol or below.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Dipole correction term in PBC 
\begin_inset Formula $2\pi d^{2}/3V$
\end_inset

 see Makov95.
 This is comparable to a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solvation energy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of a dipole in metallic cavity of volume V.
 Dipole for benzaldehyde is about 1.136 eA thus 332 * 2 * p * 1.136^2 / 3
 / 20^3 = 0.112 kcal.
 Here 332 kcal is a Coulomb interaction of two unit charges at 1 A separation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Using an iterative solver with Dirichlet boundary condition proved to be
 less efficient while leading to essentially the same observables.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The solute charge density 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

, on the other hand, is a sum of distributed electron- and localized atomic
 core densities, 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}=n_{\text{e}}+n_{\text{n}}$
\end_inset

, the latter representing atomic nuclei or effective core charges: 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{n}}(\vec{r})=\sum_{i}z_{i}\delta(\vec{r}-\vec{r}_{i})$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, we apply a simplified Ewald scheme: a convolution 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{n}}^{\prime}=p\ast n_{\text{n}}$
\end_inset

 of this singular charge density with a unit gaussian kernel 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 together with the electron charge density 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{e}}$
\end_inset

 are evaluated on the uniform grid and Poisson equation is then solved for
 the net neutral charge distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{e}}+n_{\text{n}}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 by the same technique as for the solvent charge density 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{v}}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
sic! The later change to analytically compute FT of the long-range nuclear
 field on the grid (introduced for charged solutes) does not apply here.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The resulting potential is non-singular and accounts for the Coulomb field
 of electrons, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\text{C}}\ast n_{\text{e}}$
\end_inset

, and the long range field of atomic cores, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\text{CL}}\ast n_{\text{n}}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\text{CL}}=f_{\text{C}}\ast p=\mathrm{erf}(ar)/r$
\end_inset

.
 The remaining singular short range potential of the cores, 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i}z_{i}f_{\text{CS}}(|\vec{r}-\vec{r}_{i}|)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{\text{CS}}=f_{\text{C}}-f_{\text{CL}}$
\end_inset

, is treated in the same way as the LJ field by evaluating explicit expression
 at each grid point.
 Notably, the overall method is only practical when employing effective
 core potentials in QM calculations because of the reliance on the uniform
 cartesian grid representation of electron charge density.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In DFT the electronic structure of solute in gas phase is determined by
 minimizing the Kohn--Sham energy functional with respect to the the electronic
 density 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "kochDFT"

\end_inset

.
 For brevity we express the energy as a functional of the solute charge
 density, 
\begin_inset Formula $E[n_{\text{u}}]$
\end_inset

, instead.
 The corresponding solution will be denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

.
 The distribution of the site charges of the solute force-field parameterization
 is a coarse approximation 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{n}_{\text{u}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

 of the solute charge distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

.
 Hence, RISM calculations of the excess chemical potential with the discrete
 force-field and delocalized gas-phase charge distributions as inputs will
 give two lowest approximations, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu[\bar{n}_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

, for the excess chemical potential of the solute in solvent environment.
 The two approximations for the free energy 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{MM}}=E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]+\mu[\bar{n}_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{PT1}}=E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]+\mu[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

 will be referred to as MM and PT1 in this work.
 We explain the reference to the first order perturbation theory (PT1) by
 declaring the excess chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu[n_{\text{u}}]$
\end_inset

 to be a perturbation of the energy functional 
\begin_inset Formula $E[n_{\text{u}}]$
\end_inset

 in a self-consistent field (SCF) QM+RISM model with a free energy functional
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G[n_{\text{u}}]=E[n_{\text{u}}]+\mu[n_{\text{u}}].\label{eq:free-energy-functional}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The PT1 free energy is obtained by evaluating the free energy functional
 
\begin_inset Formula $G[n_{\text{u}}]$
\end_inset

 at the unperturbed gas-phase charge distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

.
 The hybrid QM+RISM free energy functional, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:free-energy-functional"

\end_inset

, will be, in general, minimized by a different solution 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

.
 The self-consistent model and corresponding free-energy values, 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{\text{SCF}}=G[n_{\text{u}}^{(1)}]$
\end_inset

, will be annotated by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

SCF
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Further, it will be more convenient to operate with the free energy values
 offset by 
\begin_inset Formula $-E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

, the gas-phase energy of the solute: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\Delta G_{\text{MM}} & = & \mu[\bar{n}_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]\nonumber \\
\Delta G_{\text{PT1}} & = & \mu[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]\nonumber \\
\Delta G_{\text{SCF}} & = & \left(E[n_{\text{u}}^{(1)}]-E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]\right)+\mu[n_{\text{u}}^{(1)}]\label{eq:dG-models-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

The difference 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E_{\text{SCF}}=E[n_{\text{u}}^{(1)}]-E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

 in the last equation is the energy corresponding to the solute polarization
 by the solvent, a non-negative value for any 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{u}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

.
 By construction, the solvent reaction field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mu/\delta n_{\text{u}}=\phi_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

, is an electrostatic addition to the Kohn--Sham potential; the corresponding
 electric field leads to the redistribution of the electron charge density
 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}^{(1)}-n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Conversely, since 
\begin_inset Formula $G[n_{\text{u}}^{(1)}]\leq G[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

, the SCF relaxation of the excess chemical potential 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\mu_{\text{SCF}}=\mu[n_{\text{u}}^{(1)}]-\mu[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

 is necessarily a non-positive value with a magnitude larger or equal to
 that of the polarization energy: 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\mu_{\text{SCF}}\leq-\Delta E_{\text{SCF}}$
\end_inset

.
 A simplified quadratic model for the energy functionals 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 predicts the upper and lower bonds for the ratio of two relaxation terms,
 
\begin_inset Formula $-2\leq\Delta\mu_{\text{SCF}}/\Delta E_{\text{SCF}}\leq-1,$
\end_inset

 with the lower bound realized in the limiting case of a linear 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 that corresponds to a static reaction field, Appendix [FIXME].
 We will demonstrate that for organic solutes in water examined in this
 work that ratio is not very far from 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

.
 We will estimate the magnitude of the polarization term, 
\begin_inset Formula $E[n_{\text{u}}^{(1^{\prime})}]-E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]$
\end_inset

, by applying a static solvent reaction field, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\mu[\bar{n}_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]/\delta n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

, determined from the force field model of the solute to the QM system,
 thus approximating 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{\text{u}}^{(1^{\prime})}\approx n_{\text{u}}^{(1)}$
\end_inset

, and assuming a fixed ratio of the two relaxation terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Delta G_{\text{PT2}}=\Delta G_{\text{PT1}}-\left(E[n_{\text{u}}^{(1^{\prime})}]-E[n_{\text{u}}^{(0)}]\right).\label{eq:dG-models-2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The so introduced PT2 expression thus includes a term of second order in
 the solvent reaction field, though in a very approximate fashion.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An intuitive result for the reaction field contributing to the Kohn--Sham
 potential, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{\text{u}}=\delta\mu/\delta n_{\text{u}}$
\end_inset

, to be a mean Coulomb field of the solvent volume charge relies on the
 observation that HNC and KH expressions for the excess chemical potential,
 Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:mu"

\end_inset

, are path-independent work integrals 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Singer85,Kast08"

\end_inset

 and the model assumption that electrons interact with solvent sites by
 Coulomb law 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gusarov06"

\end_inset

.
 The PMV correction, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu^{\text{UC}}-\mu$
\end_inset

, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:3DRISM-UC"

\end_inset

, on the other hand, is considered an empiric post-SCF addition and not
 a part of the self-consistent free energy functional, Eq.
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:free-energy-functional"

\end_inset

.
 Such a post-SCF treatment of the PMV correction along the lines of the
